[1]
Date: Mon 28 Mar 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Bradenton Herald [edited]
<http://www.bradenton.com/mld/bradenton/11250293.htm>


Pasco girl's death may have link to E. coli outbreak
-----------------------------------------------
The state's top health official confirmed, on Mon 28 Mar 2005, that the
sudden death of a Pasco County girl is being investigated as possibly
linked to an outbreak of kidney disease caused by _E. coli_ bacteria
believed to have been contracted at a fair.

Florida Health Secretary John Agwunobi said there are 14 confirmed cases of
people who attended the Strawberry Festival in Plant City or the Central
Florida Fair in Orlando in early March 2005 who have since been sick, and
who either tested positive for _E. coli_ or a kidney disease that sometimes
results from _E. coli_ infection.

Of those 14, the majority by far are in Orange County, which includes
Orlando. Agwunobi said that 9 of the victims remain hospitalized. He
declined to say what their conditions were, but said none had died. Along
with those 14 cases, state health officials are also investigating 7
suspect cases around the state, including the death of the Pasco County
girl, in which victims may have been sickened by the _E. coli_ strain or
contracted the potentially fatal kidney disease.

He said state officials were awaiting reports from the medical examiner to
help make a determination of whether she was infected with the particular
bacterium, _E. coli_ O157:H7, or had the kidney disease that sometimes
results from it, known as hemolytic uremic syndrome, or HUS.

Local media reports said the 12-year-old girl had a high fever and
collapsed and died on Wed 23 Mar 2005. Her family told medical
investigators that she had visited the Strawberry Festival, the St.
Petersburg Times reported.

Officials have said that contact with animals in petting zoos that were at
both fairs is one possible way victims could have contracted the bacteria.
But Agwunobi cautioned on Monday [28 Mar 2005] that officials don't know
the definitive source. "We're not sure that the petting zoos have anything
to do with this outbreak," Agwunobi said. "They are one possible source
that we are investigating." Others include the possibility that tainted
food was served at the fairs or that contact with other animals, animal
waste, or even hay might have caused the sickness.

[Byline: David Rouse]

