[2]
Date: Fri 25 Mar 2005
From: E. Wayne Johnson <ewj@uiuc.edu>


The recent Florida HUS problem may or may not be a petting-zoo-_E.
coli_-related problem. Nevertheless, petting zoos do pose a significant
risk to children if precautions are not taken.

Those animal owners who exhibit animals in petting zoos do that for
commercial purposes. It is a nice thing for children to get to see and
touch animals, but the providing of access to animals in a petting zoo is
something that is done for commercial profit.

The risk of serious toxigenic _E. coli_ infection in children following
exposure to animals at petting zoos is well documented.

I consider it irresponsible for those running the petting zoos to fail to
ensure that the children wash their hands. I am offended that the petting
zoo operators "sell" the hand wipes rather than provide them as an
essential part of their service. The fact that the hand wipes are there and
are for sale does, in my opinion, constitute acknowledgement that there is
a need to wash hands, and the failure to provide them to unsuspecting and
susceptible children constitutes significant negligence.

--
E. Wayne Johnson DVM
Animal Sciences
University of Illinois
Urbana, Illinois 61801
<ewj@uiuc.edu>

[The death of the 12-year-old girl reported in the 1st posting is of
unclear etiology, but high fever is not a common manifestation of _E. coli_
O157:H7 disease. I would think her unfortunate death is of a different
etiology, despite her visit to the fair.

Regarding Dr. Johnson's comments, I personally visited the petting zoos at
the North Carolina State Fair last fall [2004], which was linked to a fair
number of _E. coli_ O157:H7 disease cases. I observed many signs regarding
the need for hand washing as well as the easy availability of both
water-based and non-aqueous forms of hand cleansing. There was no cost for
using the cleaning stations. - Mod.LL]

[OSHA does not have regulations over the animals or the workers, aside from
a requirement that a safe working area be provided. Generally, OSHA does
not regulate the zoo to the point of hand wipes. They regulate the zoo to
the point that a safe environment is provided. _E. coli_ is not on their
list. Additionally, the zoo is a private enterprise. How hand washes are to
be made available is not dictated. If the enterprising zoo elects to sell
them, it has, nevertheless, met the standard of the law. However, it was my
understanding that there were free hand wash stations available. The zoo is
not responsible for making sure the patrons use them, no more than the
department of health can force people to wash their hands after visiting
toilet facilities. - Mod.TG]
